The unified read and write interface.

Spark reads and writes data through a single, fluent interface. To read, you call spark dot read, dot format, dot option, dot load, with a path. To write, you call dataframe dot write, dot format, dot mode, dot save, with a path. And the short methods — dot csv, dot json, dot parquet, dot orc — are just aliases for that longer format-and-load form. Same plumbing, less typing.

Four formats matter for everyday Spark work.

C-S-V takes its schema from a header row, or from an explicit schema you provide. It is human-readable, but slow, and it is plain text.

Jason is inferred or explicit, and it is good for semi-structured payloads and A-P-I dumps.

Parquet embeds its schema in the file footer. It is columnar, and it is the default for analytics.

And O-R-C is the same story — schema in the footer, columnar, and common in Hadoop pipelines.

The nice thing is that the reader and the writer are symmetric. Nearly everything you learn about one applies directly to the other.
